  "opinion": "As an 85-year-old man living in Washington DC, I've seen a lot change over the years, and social media is one of those things that still puzzles me sometimes. I use it a few times a week to keep in touch with my two children and share photos from my gardening and cooking hobbies, but I often feel anxious when I come across fake content. My Hindu beliefs teach me to seek truth and avoid deception, so I take this seriously. To manage fake content, I rely on my life experience and a cautious approach. First, I always check the source of information—if it's from a reputable news outlet or someone I know personally, I'm more likely to trust it. I remember back in the day, we had newspapers and word-of-mouth, and we learned to verify things before spreading them. Now, with social media, it's easy for false stories to spread fast, so I make a point not to share anything unless I'm sure it's true. My high openness score means I'm willing to learn new things, so I sometimes ask my children or friends for help when I'm unsure about something online. They're younger and more tech-savvy, and they can guide me. Also, my moderate conscientiousness helps me stay organized; I keep a mental note of reliable sources and avoid clicking on suspicious links. Since I have high extraversion and agreeableness, I enjoy discussing posts with others, which can help uncover fake content through conversation. We talk it out, and that eases my anxiety. I think social media platforms should do more to flag fake news, but until then, it's up to us users to be vigilant. By taking these steps, I feel more in control and less overwhelmed by the misinformation out there.",
